{{Infobox language family |name=Kara |altname= = Tar Gula? |region=[[Central African Republic]] |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Central Sudanic]] |fam3=[[Bongo–Bagirmi languages|Bongo–Bagirmi]] |child1=[[Tar Gula language|Tar Gula]] |child2=? |glotto=ferg1237 |glottoname={{nowrap|Fer–Gula–Koto}} }}
The '''Kara languages''' are [[Tar Gula language|Tar Gula]] and possibly related [[Central Sudanic languages|Central Sudanic]] languages of the [[Central African Republic]]. The name ''Kara'' is used for numerous other peoples of the region, and so is often ambiguous.
''Ethnologue'' 16 lists three Kara languages, [[Tar Gula language|Gula]], [[Furu language|Furu]] (Bagero), and [[Yulu language|Yulu]] (Yulu–Binga). However, of these, Blench (2012) accepts only Gula. He places Furu with the [[Kresh language|Kresh]] dialect cluster and Yulu as an isolate within [[Bongo–Bagirmi languages|Bongo–Bagirmi]]. Nonetheless, he retain the Kara branch, also with three languages: Gula, [[Kara of Birao]], and [[Kara language (Sudan)|Kara of Sudan]]. ''Ethnologue'' treats Kara (Sudan) as a synonym of Gula, being merely the Gula spoken across the border in Sudan. The Kara of Birao it leaves [[unclassified language|unclassified]]. However, it lists Fer ''(Dam Fer, Fertit)'' as synonyms; in Blench's and earlier classifications, [[Fer language|Fer]] is a [[Bagirmi languages|Bagirmi language]], and ''Ethnologue'' does not list a separate Fer language for CAR. Thus it is possible that the Kara branch is synonymous with the Gula language.
