{{Infobox language | name = Kunza | altname = Atacama | nativename = Likanantaí | states = [[Atacama Desert]] | ethnicity = [[Atacama people]] | extinct = ca. 1950s | familycolor = American | family = [[language isolate]] | iso3 = kuz | glotto = kunz1244 | glottorefname = Kunza }}
'''Kunza''' a.k.a. '''Cunza''', also known as '''Likanantaí''', '''Lipe''', '''Ulipe''', or '''Atacameño''', is an extinct [[language isolate]] once spoken in the [[Atacama Desert]] of northern [[Chile]] and southern [[Perú]] (specifically in Peine, [[Socaire]] ([[Salar de Atacama]]), and [[Caspana]]) by the [[Atacama people|Lickan-antay]] people, who have since shifted to [[Spanish people|Spanish]].
The last Kunza speaker was found in 1949, although some have been found since according to anthropologists.{{Clarify|date=February 2009}} There are 2,000 [[Atacameño]]s (W. Adelaar).
Kaufman (1990) found a proposed connection between Kunza and the likewise unclassified [[Kanoê language|Kapixaná]] to be plausible; however, when that language was more fully described in 2004, it turned out to be an isolate.
Kunza contains a typical 5-vowel inventory: /a, e, i, o, u/. All vowels have long counterparts, and Kunza displays contrastive vowel length.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~saphon|title=SAPhon – South American Phonological Inventories|website=linguistics.berkeley.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+Consonants ! colspan="2" rowspan="2" | ! colspan="2" |[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ! colspan="2" |[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! colspan="2" |[[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! colspan="2" |[[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! colspan="2" |[[Uvular consonant|Uvular]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] !<small>plain</small> ![[Ejective consonant|<small>ejective</small>]] |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Stop consonant|Stop]] !<small>voiceless</small> |p |pʼ |t |tʼ | | | |k |kʼ |q |qʼ |ʔ |- ![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]] |b | | | | | | | | | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] | | |t͡s | |t͡ʃ |t͡ʃʼ | | | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] !<small>voiceless</small> | | |s | | | | |x | |χ | |h |- ![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]] | | | | | | | |ɣ | | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |m | |n | | | | | | | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | |l | | | |j | | | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Flap consonant|Flap]] | | |ɾ | | | | | | | | | |}
