[[File:Aljamiado.png|thumb|A passage from the Young Man's work. It is in Spanish written with Arabic script (''[[aljamiado]]'').]]
The '''Young Man of Arévalo''' ({{lang-es|el Mancebo de Arévalo}}) was a [[Morisco]] [[crypto-Muslim]] author from [[Arévalo]], [[Crown of Castile|Castile]] who was the most productive known Islamic author in Spain during the period after the [[forced conversion#Spain|forced conversion]] of Muslims there.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=170}} He traveled widely across Spain to visit crypto-Muslim communities and wrote several works about Islam which includes accounts from his travels.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}}{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}} His real identity and dates of birth and death are unknown, but most of his travels took place in the first half of the sixteenth century.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}}

== Biography ==
The Young Man was born in [[Arévalo]]{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=171}} to a mother who was converted to [[Christianity]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}} His birth date is unknown, but his youth was estimated to be in the period following the end of [[Reconquista]], marked by the [[Fall of Granada]] in 1492 and the  forced conversion of Muslims in Castile, 1500{{ndash}}1502.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}} When he was young, he traveled to virtually all parts of Spain except the seabord provinces, which was forbidden to him due to his status as [[Morisco]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}} Places he visited include [[Alcántara]], [[Almagro, Ciudad Real|Almagro]], [[Astorga, Spain|Astorga]], [[Ávila, Spain|Ávila]], [[Gandia]], [[Granada]], [[Jaén, Spain|Jaén]], [[Ocaña, Spain|Ocaña]], [[Requena, Valencia|Requena]], [[Ronda]], [[Segovia]], and [[Zaragoza]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}}{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=180}} He collaborated with [[Bray de Reminjo]], the [[faqih]] of the village of [[Cadrete]] in [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]],{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=162}} to write an Islamic religious manual called ''Brief compendium of our sacred law and [[sunnah|sunna]]'', in the 1530s. {{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}} At this point he was presumed to have been a reputable writer.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=172}} Bray de Reminjo described him as "intellectual", a Castilian from Arévalo, and described that in addition to speaking Spanish and being well-versed in ''aljamiado'', he also read Arabic, Hebrew, Greek, and Latin.{{sfn|Narváez Córdova|2006|p=491}} His works show his familiarity with the [[Quran]], the writings of [[Thomas à Kempis]], especially ''[[The Imitation of Christ]]'', as well as the medieval novel ''[[La Celestina]]''.{{sfn|Narváez Córdova|2006|p=487}} His familiarity with Christian works was likely the result of his being obligated to attend missionary sermons.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=176}}

Accounts of his travels included participating in a  secret congregational ritual prayer (''[[Salah#Prayer in congregation|salat jama'ah]]'') in [[Zaragoza]], meeting with Muslim notables and preachers, including some women, and collecting alms to go for [[hajj|pilgrimage to Mecca]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=181}} It is unclear whether he was ultimately successful in visiting Mecca,{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=173}} given that travel out of the country was illegal for Moriscos. Throughout his writings he showed deep conviction that Islam was the right faith{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=173}} and that it would triumph again in Spain within his lifetime.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=182}}

== Works ==
[[File:De Imitatione Christi 001 title page 01.jpg|thumb|upright|''[[The Imitation of Christ]]'' included passages that were likely adopted in the Young Man's ''Tafsira''.]]
He wrote at least three extant works, the ''Brief compendium of our sacred law and [[sunnah|sunna]]'' (c. 1533{{sfn|Thomas|Chesworth|2014|p=162}}), the ''[[Tafsir]]a'' (c. 1533{{sfn|Thomas|Chesworth|2014|p=165}}), and the ''Summary of the Account and Spiritual Exercise'' (c. shortly before 1550{{sfn|Thomas|Chesworth|2014|p=167}}), all written in Spanish with Arabic script (''[[aljamiado]]''), and primarily about religious topics.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=173}}<ref name="Catlos2014">{{cite book|author=Brian A. Catlos|title=Muslims of Medieval Latin Christendom, c.1050–1614|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RnU9AwAAQBAJ|date=20 March 2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-91575-5|p=281}}</ref> In addition to the religious content, the works included accounts of his travels, his meetings with other clandestine Muslims, and descriptions of their religious practices and discussions.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=162}} These accounts and reminiscences provide historians with information about the [[crypto-Muslim]] community in fifteenth-century Spain and their practices.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=179}}

The ''Brief Compendium'' is a work of [[fiqh]] (Islamic jurisprudence), covering topics of ''[[ibadah]]'' (Islamic acts of worship) and [[Islamic economics]].{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=161}} It was written in collaboration with Bray de Reminjo, marking a rare collaboration between Castilian (represented by the Young Man) and Aragonese (by Bray) Muslim traditions.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=121}} The ''Tafsira'' is a ''[[tafsir]]'' or a commentary of the Quran.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=174}} The ''Summary'' is a religious book on topics of devotion and piety.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=173}}

Spanish scholar [[Pascual de Gayangos y Arce]] mentioned in 1839 of having seen an additional work he called ''The Pilgrimage of the Young Man'' in Madrid, but this work is now lost.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=193}}{{sfn|Narváez Córdova|2006|p=490}}

In 1980, Spanish author Gregorio Fonseca Antuña discovered close similarities between passages in the ''Summary'' and passages from [[Thomas à Kempis]]'s 15th-century work ''[[The Imitation of Christ]]'', a Christian [[devotional book]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=174}} The passages were often adapted to replace specific Christian contexts and features with Islamic ones, while keeping the spiritual and moral meaning intact.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=176}} These similarities occur frequently throughout the book, including in long passages.{{sfn|Thomas|Chesworth|2014|p=167}}{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=174}} According to historian L. P. Harvey, Kempis' influence is "established beyond doubt",{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=174}} and could not have been due to chance.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=175}} The Young Man did not cite Kempis as sources for the passages, and frequently attributed the passages to Islamic scholars such as [[al-Ghazali]] and [[Ibn Arabi]], misleadingly.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=176}} The adaptation of Christian devotional literature in his Islamic work could be the result of his being obligated to attend missionary sermons, and a lack of access to actual Islamic literature.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=176}} In contrast to the ''Summary'', the Young Man's other works show considerable originality.{{sfn|Thomas|Chesworth|2014|p=168}}

== Possible identity ==
Historian [[L. P. Harvey]] proposed that the Young Man of Arévalo might have been the same person as Agustín de Ribera, a Morisco from Arévalo who claimed to be a prophet and had the epithet of ''el mozo'' (the lad), although he admitted that the theory had a lot of difficulties that he had not resolved.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=171}} Agustín was arrested by the [[Spanish Inquisition]] in 1540 and records from his interrogation survived.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=111–112}}

== Legacy ==
The Young Man's works became known throughout the Morisco community, and he achieved fame as a scholar.{{sfn|Thomas|Chesworth|2014|p=160}} His works were copied up to the end of the sixteenth century, and cited by Morisco authors up to the beginning of the seventeenth century, just before the [[expulsion of the Moriscos]].{{sfn|Thomas|Chesworth|2014|p=160}}

He was the most productive known Islamic author in Spain during the period after the [[forced conversion#Spain|forced conversion]] of Muslims there,{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=170}} today historians often single him out for attention in studies of Morisco literature in this period. {{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=171}}

